<DOC><DOCNO> AP890714-0105 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1218EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-USSoldiers-Honduras     07-14 0277</FIRST><SECOND>PM-US Soldiers-Honduras,260</SECOND><HEAD>Four US Soldiers Injured In Honduras Evacuated to Texas</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Four U.S. soldiers who were seriously injuredin a Honduras bomb blast have been evacuated to an Army medicalcenter in Texas, the Pentagon said today.   One of the four, Spec. Michael R. Barge, 22, of Cincinnati, Ohio,was listed in ``critical but stable'' condition, the Pentagon said.   Three others who were also injured in the blast, but reported tobe in good condition, will remain in a medical center at Soto CanoAir Base in Honduras, the Pentagon said.   The seven were hit when a homemade bomb exploded outside adiscotheque in the northern town of La Ceiba, located some 200 milesnorth of Tegucigalpa.   Two others in the group escaped injury.   No one has claimed responsibility for the fourth attack on U.S.troops in Honduras since Feb. 1.   The soldiers, all assigned to the 459th Military Police Company,are based at Fort Davis in Panama, the Pentagon said.   They were part of a convoy of about 150 Americans returning froma road-building exercise with Honduran troops that had stopped at LaCeiba for the night.   According to the Pentagon, those listed in serious condition andevacuated to Brooke Army Medical Center at Fort Sam Houston in Texasare:   Staff Sgt. Robert P. Nelson, 27, of Ontario, Calif.; Pfc. TerryP. Posey, 19, of Cutoff., La.; Pfc. John M. Wollenfang, 26, ofVerona., Wis.   Those listed in good condition, and remaining in Honduras, are:   1st Lieut. Alberto Soto, 23, of New York, N.Y.; Staff Sgt. JohnC. Ford, 26, of Flint, Mich.; Pfc. Robert A. Engberts, 21, ofKalamazoo, Mich.</TEXT></DOC>